annotations:
Hold me while you can, hold me while you can
 I’ll still be your friend, you’ll come back again

In relationships, and especially situationships, there is a pattern of loving someone until you love someone else… And I think that is exactly the feeling this song is describing. You hold someone until their in the arms of another and you cherish that time with them… but you still know that one day, they will love someone else.
And you might still be friends or friends but at the end of the day, you both know that it will never work out.
Hope you understand we won’t go as planned
Basically starting out the song saying the relationship that they are in is destined for failure…

description.plain:
“Free Room” by singer Ravyn Lenae is a modern and upbeat song that can be categorised as R&B or pop. The backing track, produced by frequent collaborator and fellow member of music collaborative group Zero Fatigue; Monte Booker is not explicitly one genre of music but instead floats between EDM and Pop.

The R&B element is most prevalently explored by Lenae herself, who through her rhythmic speech in the intro and spoken verses throughout elevate this track to the funky and energetic song that it is. This as an aggregate contribute to why “Free Room” is one of Lenae’s most successful songs thus far.

description.plain:
“Sticky” is the lead single off Ravyn Lenae’s sophomore project, Crush. Teaming up with Compton-raised singer-songwriter and producer Steve Lacy, the duo’s R&B, funk, and alternative waves combine perfectly for a groovy track about the unpredictability of a love interest.

In a now-deleted tweet, Lacy revealed that “Sticky” is the “only iPhone beat on the project so that [one’s] special.”

annotations: Zigzag, circus

Zigzag is just like a super crazy pattern, and I imagine a maze of us running and me trying to catch him. He’s turning every corner and I can’t grab him. And then a circus it’s just like wild. You have elephants, and fire, and so many crazy things happening. So, to pair both of those together, imagine a circus in a zig-zag pattern…it’s just like wild, and that’s what I feel is happening in the relationship and in my mind.
You could treat me fair

In a relationship, I require honesty. And I feel like that’s the hardest thing for people to do, be transparent. Even if it’s not serious. You know, people have a tendency to maybe lie or not tell the whole truth maybe because they think they’re sparing someone’s feelings when they’re really not. I require that. I require respect. I think when in a relationship, in order to love each other properly, you have to respect each other. So, talking to each other in a nice way, communicating effectively. Things that seems to be really hard for people, and it’s so easy when you really care about the person.

You know I cannot shake you
 You know I cannot break you
The reason why I can’t break away in this song is because I don’t wanna be lonely. I don’t wanna be by myself and feel all those emotions of this person did me dirty and I let them do me dirty.
Something told me I would end up lonely

With that line, I really wanted to paint the picture of a relationship changing and the dynamics being a little weird, or different from how they were before. And kind of witnessing from start to finish, or middle, how has this relationship grown or not grown, or how has this person changed? So, “I would end up lonely,” means that yeah, I had that gut feeling in beginning, but I had hope that it would change or that it would get better, but I knew I would end up myself or not feeling loved.

You got me wondering where the spunk went
 Where the funk went
 Not who I’m in love with

I like to imagine those lyrics as an internal conversation because me, I’m super non-confrontational. I don’t like to argue, I don’t like to talk about my feelings, and stuff. Ew. So, yeah. I think this whole song is me battling with myself. Like, “Ugh, I know this guy doesn’t like me, but I really can’t say anything to him because I don’t wanna piss him off.”
Spinning, spinning ’round and ’round
This is like that kid-like innocence, or like confusion, where you’re just being a kid and not knowing what you’re getting yourself into, but you just wanna spin around and round.

What did you do?
 Got me confused-used

So, I really wanted to start the song with the main feeling of being confused.  Like, I’m going crazy over you and I don’t know why. You got me confused because one day you love me and the next day you hate me a little bit.

annotations:
Don’t care what nobody say
 A thousand miles in the way
 You pick the time and the day
 I got it, I got it

Ravyn is dismissing any negative comments outsiders might have in regards to her long distance virtual relationship. Here she displays her love by letting her lover decide when and where they should meet up, and that she will make the meeting happen.

Don’t fade away, my love
 In cyberspace, my love
 One click away from you
 Don’t fade away

She speaks to cyberspace – her lover lives in this void. They are “a click away,” they are “inside the space.” She hopes they will be something real to her one day, and not just disappear along with the screen.

You knew it right from the start
 Computer love is not smart
 Don’t lose it, don’t break my heart
 Don’t break my heart (Don’t break my heart)

“Computer love” is indeed, not a smart route. Living in a society where digital representations of oneself  are curated and one-dimensional – it might lead to others idealizing your existence. Ravyn knows this from the beginning and hopes her lover will match up to her expectations, thus not breaking her heart.

When will I meet you? I’m down to see you
 I wanna see you right now
 It’s been a year now, I shed a tear down
 My face dripping, drown my feelings
 Enter this one text, I wonder what is next?
 Will I catch real feelings for you?
 Or could this be pointless? I should’ve avoided this
 But what if this real?

Here, Ravyn outlines the agonies she feels re: her lover’s distance. She then ponders whether her feelings are irrational considering they have yet to meet and that this is all just an online infatuation. A glimmer of hope remains as she acknowledges that the feelings, though currently intangible, could truly develop.

description.plain: This song by Ravyn Lenae and Steve Lacy features them as friends who are in a quasi-romantic relationship. Ravyn expresses her frustration at Steve’s unwillingness to commit fully to their relationship, instead he claims that he is trying to protect their friendship by not committing to her. As the song progresses, Ravyn becomes more desperate, asking for a “4 leaf clover,” a symbol of luck, to help her convince Steve to commit to their romantic relationship.
